{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480049"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:36:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:36:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"6"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/6"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.46,0.37,0.01,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105587"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"6"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88012"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35301"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38458"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42950"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105587"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of feeling generally unwell, with shortness of breath and cough. He has decreased exercise tolerance and can only walk 20m before becoming short of breath. He has a medical history of ischaemic heart disease, hypertension, previous deep vein thrombosis (DVT) following knee replacement 10 years ago, and significant alcohol use. His medications include aspirin, ramipril, and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 96/min, blood pressure 145/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 93% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has a displaced apex beat, reduced chest expansion, and a dull percussion note at the base of the lungs bilaterally. He has bilateral leg oedema to the mid calf and mildly tender calves on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation for his shortness of breath?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["D-dimer test","Chest X-ray","Echocardiogram","Full blood count","Lower limb DVT ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation suggests a clinical picture of decompensated heart failure with fluid overload causing peripheral oedema and pulmonary oedema. The aetiology of his heart failure is likely ischaemic heart disease and hypertension. The trigger for decompensation is currently unclear but may include infection (bacterial or viral), an ischemic event, anaemia, or non-adherence to medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe next investigation should be a \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the best way to confirm a diagnosis of pulmonary oedema. Chest x-ray findings in pulmonary oedema include increased alveolar markings, Kerley B lines, and bilateral pleural effusions (which manifest as the blunting of costophrenic angles). The patient is also likely to have cardiomegaly, given he has a displaced apex beat clinically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile an \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is best to further characterise the heart failure, by assessing the ejection fraction and looking for any valvular pathology, the current issue is most likely pulmonary oedema and this diagnosis should be confirmed first, so that prompt treatment with diuresis can be initiated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efull blood count\u003C/strong\u003E will not be helpful in diagnosing pulmonary oedema which is his current acute problem. It may reveal other exacerbating conditions such as anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a pulmonary embolus can cause shortness of breath and reduced oxygen saturation, a pulmonary embolus does not explain the displaced apex beat, reduced chest expansion, and dull percussion note at the base of the lungs bilaterally. The patient also has no features of a lower limb DVT (no erythema, no unilateral swelling or pain) which make a \u003Cstrong\u003EDVT ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E not useful in this patient. It is also important to note that patients with peripheral oedema can have mild calf tenderness, however this is less likely to be indicative of DVT in this patient in the absence of unilateral, warm, erythematous leg swelling, or risk factors for DVT (e.g. immobility, cancer).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther, a \u003Cstrong\u003ED-dimer test\u003C/strong\u003E would be unhelpful in this scenario. While the patient has risk factors for pulmonary embolism including previous DVT, the clinical features are more suggestive of heart failure. Additionally, D-dimer testing has poor specificity in older patients and those with comorbidities, leading to many false positive results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chest x-ray findings in pulmonary oedema: increased alveolar markings, Kerley B lines, bilateral pleural effusions","Initial investigation in suspected heart failure should focus on confirming pulmonary oedema to guide immediate management","D-dimer testing has poor specificity in older patients and those with comorbidities"],"references":["2021 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of acute and chronic heart failure: Developed by the Task Force for the diagnosis and treatment of acute and chronic heart failure of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC) With the special contribution of the Heart Failure Association (HFA) of the ESC (https://academic.oup.com/eurheartj/article/42/36/3599/6358045)","National Heart Foundation of Australia and Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Guidelines for the Prevention, Detection, and Management of Heart Failure in Australia 2018 (https://www.heartlungcirc.org/article/S1443-9506(18)31777-3/fulltext)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88012"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"6"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88012"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-10T20:44:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-10T20:45:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105587"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"